{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609788"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:50:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:50:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16123"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16123"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.3,0.35,0.2,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63978"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8814"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49408"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5119"},{"type":"tags","id":"7056"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21033"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63978"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic development, the external genitalia undergo differentiation in response to androgens. In typical male development, this process involves the fusion of labioscrotal folds to form the scrotum and the elongation and development of the penis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes when external genitalia differentiation is completed in typical male development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Week 14","Week 15","Week 16","Week 17","Week 18"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMale external genitalia differentiation is completed by \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek 14\u003C/strong\u003E of embryonic development. This process is dependent on testosterone and dihydrotestosterone produced by the fetal testes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe development continues beyond \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek 15\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek 16\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek 17\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek 18\u003C/strong\u003E, but these timepoints are after the completion of the critical differentiation period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe process begins around week 8 when androgens start influencing the development of external genitalia. The genital tubercle elongates to form the penis, the urethral folds fuse to form the penile urethra, and the labioscrotal swellings fuse to form the scrotum. All these changes are complete by week 14.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Male external genitalia development is testosterone-dependent and completes by week 14 of embryonic development.","The critical period for male external genitalia differentiation occurs between weeks 8-14 of development."],"references":["Hutson JM, Li R, Southwell BR, Petersen BL, Thorup J, Cortes D. Germ cell development in the postnatal testis: the key to prevent malignancy in cryptorchidism? Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2013 Jan 3;3:176. doi: 10.3389/fendo.2012.00176. PMID: 23316184; PMCID: PMC3539691","P A A, Arbor TC, Krishan K. Embryology, Sexual Development. [Updated 2023 Aug 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557601/","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49408"